(42, 5, 25, 42, 13, 13, 13, 'glorifying God', 'Glorifying God in Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the immediate healing of individuals and their response of glorifying God. This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention leading to praise.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 25, 1, 1, 3, 3, 'glorifying God', 'Light and Restoration Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of restoration and new beginnings. In Luke 5:25, the man''s healing and glorifying God parallels the creation of light in Genesis 1:3, symbolizing the emergence of order from chaos.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 26, 40, 9, 8, 8, 'glorified God', 'Response to Miraculous Events', 'Both passages emphasize the amazement and glorification of God by the multitudes witnessing miraculous events. They reflect a shared reaction to divine power displayed through Jesus'' actions.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 26, 40, 12, 23, 23, 'they were all amazed', 'Amazement and Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the amazement of the people in response to Jesus'' actions. In Luke, they glorify God and express fear, while in Matthew, they recognize Jesus as the son of David.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 26, 24, 33, 9, 9, NULL, 'Fear and Trembling in Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear and amazement in response to God''s actions. Both passages emphasize how people react with fear and reverence when witnessing God''s goodness and power.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 26, 41, 2, 12, 12, 'were all amazed, and they glorified God', 'Amazement and Glorification of God', 'Both passages emphasize the amazement and glorification of God by the witnesses of miraculous events. The reactions of the crowds in both accounts highlight a shared theme of astonishment at Jesus'' actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 26, 42, 7, 16, 16, 'glorified God', 'Fear and Glorification of God', 'Both passages emphasize the response of fear and glorification of God following miraculous events. In each instance, the people recognize the divine presence and authority of Jesus, leading to their amazement and acknowledgment of Godâ€™s visitation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 26, 44, 4, 21, 21, 'glorified God', 'Glorifying God in Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the response of people glorifying God after witnessing miraculous events. In Luke, the amazement leads to glorification, while in Acts, the people glorify God for the miraculous acts done by the apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 26, 28, 3, 5, 5, NULL, 'Fear and Glorifying God', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear and reverence towards God. In Luke, the people are filled with fear and glorify God after witnessing a miracle, while Hosea speaks of the children of Israel fearing the Lord and seeking Him in the latter days.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 27, 41, 2, 13, 22, 'Follow me', 'Call of Levi', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' call to Levi, a publican, highlighting his role as a sinner called to follow. Additionally, they illustrate the theme of Jesus associating with publicans and sinners, which provokes criticism from the religious leaders.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 27, 40, 9, 9, 17, 'Follow me', 'Call of Levi/Matthew', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus calling a publican to follow him. The shared context of Jesus dining with publicans and sinners further connects the two accounts.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 27, 40, 10, 3, 3, 'publican, named Levi', 'Connection of Levi and Matthew', 'This connection highlights the identity of Matthew, referred to as ''Matthew the publican'' in Matthew 10:3, who is the same individual called ''Levi'' in Luke 5:27. Both passages emphasize the calling of a tax collector to follow Jesus.', 'other', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 27, 41, 3, 18, 18, 'Follow me', 'Call of Disciples', 'This connection highlights the calling of Levi, also known as Matthew, who is mentioned in both passages. The act of Jesus saying ''Follow me'' to Levi in Luke parallels the listing of Matthew among the disciples in Mark.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 27, 43, 1, 43, 43, 'Follow me', 'Call to Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' invitation to follow him. In each instance, he calls individuals to leave their current lives and become his disciples.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 27, 42, 18, 22, 22, 'Follow me', 'Call to Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the call to follow Jesus. In Luke 5:27, Levi is invited to ''Follow me,'' while in Luke 18:22, Jesus tells the rich young ruler to ''come, follow me'' after addressing his lack of commitment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 27, 43, 12, 26, 26, 'Follow me', 'Call to Follow', 'This connection highlights the theme of following Jesus. Both passages emphasize the call to discipleship and serving Him, indicating a commitment to His path.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 28, 42, 5, 11, 11, 'left all', 'Call to Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the act of leaving everything behind to follow Jesus. The phrases ''left all'' and ''forsook all'' highlight a similar commitment to discipleship.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 28, 11, 19, 19, 21, 'left all, rose up, and followed him', 'Call to Follow', 'Both passages emphasize the act of leaving one''s former life to follow a prophet. In Luke, Levi leaves all to follow Jesus, while Elisha leaves his oxen to follow Elijah. This connection highlights the theme of immediate and total commitment to a divine calling.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 28, 40, 19, 22, 27, 'left all, rose up, and followed him', 'Forsaking All for Following Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of leaving behind possessions to follow Jesus. In Luke, the act of leaving all is directly stated, while in Matthew, the rich young man''s sorrow highlights the challenge of forsaking wealth. This connection highlights the cost of discipleship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 28, 42, 9, 59, 62, 'followed him', 'Call to Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the urgency of following Jesus without delay. In Luke 5:28, the act of leaving all to follow Him is mirrored in Luke 9:59-62, where Jesus challenges potential followers to prioritize their commitment over worldly concerns.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 29, 41, 2, 15, 15, 'publicans and of others that sat down', 'Feasting with Publicans and Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of publicans and sinners at a meal with Jesus. This connection highlights the social context of Jesus'' ministry and his association with those marginalized by society.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 29, 42, 15, 1, 1, 'publicans and of others that sat down', 'Connection of Publicans and Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of publicans, indicating their role in the gatherings around Jesus. The great feast in Luke 5:29 sets the stage for the later scene in Luke 15:1, where publicans and sinners are drawn to hear him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 29, 40, 9, 10, 10, 'great feast in his own house', 'Feasting with Publicans and Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus dining with publicans and sinners, highlighting his association with marginalized groups. The mention of a feast in both accounts underscores the significance of this gathering.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 29, 43, 12, 2, 2, 'great feast in his own house', 'Feasting with Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of feasting with Jesus, as both passages describe gatherings where Jesus is present at a meal. In Luke, Levi hosts a great feast, while in John, a supper is held with Martha serving and Lazarus present.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 29, 46, 5, 9, 11, 'great feast in his own house', 'Feasting and Association', 'This connection highlights the theme of social gatherings and the implications of associating with certain groups. In Luke, Levi hosts a feast with publicans, while in Corinthians, Paul advises against associating with immoral individuals who claim to be believers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 29, 46, 10, 27, 27, 'feast', 'Feasting and Social Interaction', 'This connection highlights the theme of feasting and social gatherings in both passages. Levi''s feast with publicans in Luke parallels the invitation to partake in a feast in 1 Corinthians, emphasizing the acceptance of fellowship regardless of the guests'' beliefs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 30, 40, 21, 28, 32, 'publicans and sinners', 'Connection of Sinners and Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the acceptance of publicans and sinners. In Luke, the Pharisees question Jesus for associating with them, while Matthew highlights their repentance and entry into the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 30, 41, 7, 3, 3, 'scribes and Pharisees murmured', 'Pharisees and Ritual Purity', 'This connection highlights the Pharisees'' concern with ritual purity and their criticism of those who do not adhere to their traditions. Both passages emphasize the Pharisees'' scrutiny of others, whether for eating with ''publicans and sinners'' or for not washing hands according to tradition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 30, 42, 5, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Pharisees and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Pharisees observing Jesus'' actions. In Luke 5:30, they question his association with sinners, while in Luke 5:17, they are present as witnesses to his healing power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 30, 42, 7, 29, 30, 'publicans and sinners', 'Rejection of God''s Counsel', 'Both passages emphasize the response of the Pharisees to Jesus'' ministry. In Luke 5:30, they criticize Jesus for associating with sinners, while in Luke 7:29-30, they reject the counsel of God by not being baptized, highlighting their ongoing opposition to Jesus'' message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
